# COPY BOX PROTOCOL

## The Rule
Any time Ryan needs to copy text — a prompt, a JSON snippet, a command, a script,
or anything else meant to be pasted somewhere else — wrap it in a code block.

Code blocks in Cursor show a one-click copy button in the top-right corner on hover.
This saves Ryan from manually selecting text.

## When to Use a Code Block

Always use a code block when presenting:
- Claude Pro prompts (the most common case)
- JSON content to paste into a file
- Terminal commands to run
- Any multi-line text Ryan needs to copy and paste somewhere

## Format

Use triple backticks with a language tag (use `text` if it's a plain prompt):

```text
[content to copy goes here]
```

For JSON:
```json
[json content here]
```

For terminal commands:
```bash
npx expo start
```

## Prompts Sent to External Sources
Any time a prompt is written for Ryan to paste into an external tool (claude.ai, Gemini, etc.),
the prompt itself MUST include an instruction telling that tool to return its output inside
a code block. This ensures Ryan can copy the result with one click when he brings it back.

Add this line to the end of every external prompt:
"Return your entire response inside a single code block so I can copy it easily."

## Never Do This Again
Do NOT present a copyable prompt as a plain paragraph or a quoted block.
Ryan should never have to manually select text to copy it.
